Description: The dopaminergic neurons are in the substantia nigra and ventral tegmental area (VTA). L-phenylalanine is converted into L-tyrosine by the enzyme phenylalanine hydroxylase. L-tyrosine is then converted into L-DOPA by the enzyme tyrosine hydroxylase. L-DOPA is then converted into dopamine by the enzyme aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase. Dopamine is removed from the synaptic cleft by the dopamine transporter (DAT). Dopamine is degraded by monoamine oxidase A and B, catechol-O-methyl transferase (COMT), and aldehyde dehydrogenase (ALDH), in succession. The dopamine receptors are categorized into a D1-like family (including D1 and D5) and a D2-like family (including D2, D3, and D4). The D2 receptors are the best studied.

Description: Catechol-o-methyltransferase gene, codes for the COMT enzyme that uses methyl groups to inactivate dopamine, epinephrine, norepinephrine, and estrogen, primarily. COMT is particularly important for the prefrontal cortex of the brain (where e.g. the dopamine transporter is less active). Broadly, you have enhanced COMT activity, leading to a lower availability of dopamine and norepinephrine in the brain. This gene, alone, should make you more daring, less neurotic, and less able to maintain consistency with long-term goals.

GenotypeDescription: You carry the notorious ‘warrior’ genotype at this SNP. The alleles are the minor allele A (called ‘met’ type, for methionine) and the major allele G (called ‘val’ for valine). The met type has also been called ‘the worrier,’ while the val type has been called ‘the warrior.’ Homozygotes for A (‘worriers’) experience about a 40% reduced enzyme activity, leading to greater neurotransmitter presence in the brain. They have better working memories, exhibit better reading comprehension, they may have higher IQs, and they get more pleasure from experiences. These titles are a bit misleading, as there are advantages to both homozygote phenotypes. It appears that A homozygotes may be better at long-term goal accomplishment, essentially, due to greater neuroticism.

Description: The neurotransmitter serotonin is produced from the amino acid L-tryptophan. Using the enzyme tryptophan hydroxylase 2 (TPH2), it is converted into 5-hydroxytryptophan (5-HTP), which is then converted to 5-HT (serotonin) by amino acid decarboxylase. Serotonin is originally located in the raphe nuclei in the brain stem from where it is communicated across the brain through its axons. It is broken down by the serotonin transporter (SERT) and by the plasma membrane monoamine transporter (PMAT). PMAT is newly discovered. It is encoded by the gene SLC29A4, but not much is known about its variants. SERT is the target of the SSRI drugs, which inhibit its function, thereby allowing serotonin to remain in the synaptic cleft. Most of the studies on the genetics of serotonin regard the functions of the SERT protein, which was being studied as early as the 1990’s.
This gene codes for the enzyme aromatic l-amino acid decarboxylase, which is involved in turning L-DOPA into dopamine and 5-HTP into serotonin.

Description: gene: MAOA is an enzyme, encoded by the MAOA gene, that degrades all the monoamine neurotransmitters (dopamine, norepinephrine, and serotonin) through oxidative deamination. When the enzyme is overexpressed, we experience lower monoamine neurotransmitter levels. The enzyme is the target of an older class of antidepressants called monoamine oxidase inhibitors (MAOIs). Because these drugs are unselective (they raise levels of all three monoamine neurotransmitters), and because of their serious side effects, they are no longer favored by psychiatrists. Unfortunately, 23andMe does not genotype the most studied SNPs of this gene.

Description: Glutamate is the primary excitatory neurotransmitter in the nervous system. It is synthesized from glutamine by the enzyme glutaminase. It is degraded by glutamate decarboxylase, which transforms it into gamma-Aminobutyric acid (GABA). Glutamate has four receptor classes: AMPA, NMDA, metabotropic glutamate, and kainate receptors. It is moved across membranes by the two glutamate transporters, the excitatory amino acid transporter (EAAT) and the vesicular glutamate transporter (VGLUT). If it is not transported, glutamate can become neurotoxic due to its excitatory effect.

This gene codes for the glutamine receptor 1, belonging to the AMPA class of glutaminergic receptors. There has been a history of research that has unsuccessfully attempted to link this gene to schizophrenia.

Description: As a neurotransmitter, histamine is produced in histaminergic neurons from the hypothalamus. It is critical to circadian function, promoting alertness and arousal, which is why some anti-histamines that cross the blood-brain barrier (antagonists of the H1 receptor) produce drowsiness. Histamine (particularly the H3 receptor) is also implicated in the development of migraines.
